  "link": "https:\/\/murphlaw.net\/success\/singleton-v-hoag\/",
  "title": { "rendered": "Singleton v. Hoag" },
  "content": {
    "rendered": "<div id=\"pl-277\" class=\"panel-layout\">\n<div id=\"pg-277-0\" class=\"panel-grid panel-no-style\">\n<div id=\"pgc-277-0-0\" class=\"panel-grid-cell\" data-weight=\"1\"><\/div>\n<\/div>\n<div id=\"pg-277-1\" class=\"panel-grid panel-no-style\" data-style=\"{&quot;background_image_repeat&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;no_margin&quot;:&quot;&quot;}\">\n<div id=\"pgc-277-1-0\" class=\"panel-grid-cell\" data-weight=\"0.5\">\n<div id=\"panel-277-1-0-0\" class=\"so-panel widget widget_sow-editor panel-first-child panel-last-child\" data-index=\"1\" data-style=\"{&quot;background_image_attachment&quot;:false,&quot;background_display&quot;:&quot;tile&quot;}\">\n<div class=\"so-widget-sow-editor so-widget-sow-editor-base\">\n<div class=\"siteorigin-widget-tinymce textwidget\">\n<p><a href=\"https:\/\/murphlaw.net\/wp-content\/uploads\/2016\/02\/IMG_3197.jpg\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\" wp-image-845 alignright\" src=\"https:\/\/murphlaw.net\/wp-content\/uploads\/2016\/02\/IMG_3197.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"721\" height=\"396\" srcset=\"https:\/\/murphlaw.net\/wp-content\/uploads\/2016\/02\/IMG_3197.jpg 3061w, https:\/\/murphlaw.net\/wp-content\/uploads\/2016\/02\/IMG_3197-300x165.jpg 300w, https:\/\/murphlaw.net\/wp-content\/uploads\/2016\/02\/IMG_3197-768x422.jpg 768w, https:\/\/murphlaw.net\/wp-content\/uploads\/2016\/02\/IMG_3197-1024x563.jpg 1024w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 721px) 100vw, 721px\" \/><\/a>In <em>Singleton v. Hoag<\/em>, I had the case ordered into arbitration before the American Arbitration Association. I represented a general partner and his company with claims brought against him by seven plaintiffs, which also included Superior Court Judge Raymond Cardenas. Plaintiffs sued my client for breach of contract, fraud, emotional distress, breach of fiduciary duty, and accounting.<\/p>\n<p>Plaintiffs sought damages against my client in excess of $1,600,000. I obtained a defense verdict for my client&#8217;s company.<\/p>\n<\/div>\n<\/div>\n<\/div>\n<\/div>\n<div id=\"pgc-277-1-1\" class=\"panel-grid-cell\" data-weight=\"0.5\">\n<div id=\"panel-277-1-1-0\" class=\"so-panel widget widget_sow-image panel-first-child panel-last-child\" data-index=\"2\" data-style=\"{&quot;background_display&quot;:&quot;tile&quot;}\"><\/div>\n<\/div>\n<\/div>\n<\/div>\n",
    "protected": false
  },
  "excerpt": {
    "rendered": "<p>In Singleton v. Hoag, I had the case ordered into arbitration before the American Arbitration Association. I represented a general partner and his company with claims brought against him by seven plaintiffs, which also included Superior Court Judge Raymond Cardenas. Plaintiffs sued my client for breach of contract, fraud, emotional distress, breach of fiduciary duty, and accounting. Plaintiffs sought damages against my client in excess of $1,600,000. I obtained a defense verdict for my client&#8217;s company.<\/p>\n",
    "protected": false
  },
